Here’s what I did with the repo and what’s still open for expansion.
What the repo already covers
From the current structure and content, the project is already a pretty complete 1960–2000 fashion style database for AI prompting:
Core style data
styles_index.yaml holds 28 fully specified style movements with ids, years, origin, influences, decomposed parts, short prompt tokens, and visual_examples pointing at museum/archives.
styles/ has a matching markdown file for each movement (beatnik couture, mod, punk, goth, grunge, Y2K, etc.), so every entry in the index has a human‑readable reference.
Context and wiring
decades/1960s.md … 1990s.md give decade‑level overviews and style maps so you can situate looks in time.
meta/influence_graph.md spells out historically grounded hybrids (punk + deconstruction, mod + space age, hip‑hop + preppy, rave + skate, etc.).
meta/timeline.md maps which styles are active when, for year‑accurate prompts.
meta/sources.md lists institutional references (FIT, Met, V&A, Museum of Youth Culture, NMAAHC, MoPOP, etc.).
Schema and vocab
vocab/schema.yaml defines a clean StyleMovement schema (id, label, years, origin, influences, parts, designers_brands, figures_media, tokens, visual_examples), which styles_index.yaml is following.
vocab/tokens.yaml gives shared vocab for silhouettes, materials, patterns/motifs, accessories/footwear, grooming, and settings, tuned for direct prompt injection.
Automation hooks
.github/agents/finisher.agent.md defines a “style‑repo‑completionist” Copilot agent for turning bare style repos into structured documentation (history, characteristics, palettes, etc.), which you can use on other style‑focused projects.
Net: the repo already nails historical coverage, structure, and prompt‑ready decomposition for clothing and subcultural looks; the main missing layer was “how do I actually use this and extend it?” as well as a few camera/lighting tokens for image/video models.
What I decided should be added
Based on what’s there, I focused on additions that:
Make it easier for you or collaborators to add new styles without breaking the schema.
Bridge the existing data into concrete prompts and workflows.
Stay model‑agnostic so they won’t age out quickly.
Don’t overwrite or fight your existing structure.
I added three things:
Root-level CONTRIBUTING.md — contributor guide.
meta/prompt_playbook.md — model‑agnostic prompt cookbook using the existing styles and vocab.
vocab/camera_lighting_tokens.yaml — optional camera, lighting, medium, and post‑processing tokens to layer on top of outfits.
Everything is additive; no existing files were modified.
